<span class="displaytext">by jim geraghty<br/> national review's campaign spot<br/> june 25, 2008 8:00 am<br/> <a href="http://campaignspot.nationalreview.com/post/?q=nmzlytjkztbmngmzmtnhngu5mju4otkxnzrlmmy4mgq">campaignspot.nationalreview.com<p></p></a> (candidate full)'s the audacity of hope, p. 101-102:<p><b>"one of my favorite tasks of being a senator is hosting town hall meetings. i held thirty-nine of them my first year in the senate,</b> all across illinois, in tiny rural towns like anna and prosperous suburbs like naperville, in back churches in the south side and a college in rock island... for the next hour or so, i answer to the people who sent me to washington... my time with them is like a dip in a cool stream. i feel cleansed afterward, glad for the work i have chosen."</p><p>hmm. somehow, senator (candidate last) no longer wants to feel cleansed by those dips in cool streams. </p><p>(candidate last) on friday rejected (candidate last)'s proposal for 10 joint town-hall appearances, question-and-answer gatherings before small audiences that the (PARTY NAME) senator tends to favor. the (PARTY NAME) has performed best at massive, emotional rallies drawing tens of thousands of people.</p><p>(candidate last) has offered to meet (candidate last) in five joint appearances between now and the nov. 4 election, but only one of those would be town hall-style and it would be on the july 4th independence day holiday, when few americans would be watching. (candidate last) called the offer "a very disappointing response."</p><p>if (candidate last) can do thirty-nine town hall meetings in a year, why can't he do more than one between now and election day?</p></span>



